  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Integrating TB with MCH services in Malawi</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Tuberculosis (TB) is treatable, but is a leading cause of death in Malawi because less than half of all TB cases are detected. Pregnant women with TB are twice as likely to give birth to a premature or a small baby and four times more likely than healthy women to die during childbirth. TB screening is not part of maternal and child health services in Malawi. However, because these services are well-used, they provide a good opportunity to identify women and children with TB. This project will teach people to recognise the symptoms of TB and to get the necessary treatment. It will also raise awareness of how to prevent the disease. Health workers will be trained to screen women during antenatal visits and to screen children when they attend for routine care. Those with signs of TB will be helped to travel to health centres for diagnostic tests and treatment. The project will document the process and show how addressing TB and maternal and child health together can improve the health of women and children.</narrative>
  </description>
